[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1462},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F12\u002F19\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F12\u002F19\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F12\u002F19\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F12\u002F19\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro\u002F":1437,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F12\u002F19\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro\u002F":1446},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20211219\u002F3830068067\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1420,"date":1421,"description":1422,"extension":1423,"lang":1424,"meta":1425,"navigation":135,"path":1426,"readingMinutes":1427,"seo":1428,"standalone":1429,"stem":1430,"tags":1431,"tldr":1433,"updated":1434,"url":1435,"__hash__":1436},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Ffunctional-programming-in-javascript-intro.md","A Friendly Intro to Functional Programming in JavaScript","1001591722",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1407},"minimark",[11,18,23,26,30,33,36,39,47,50,58,163,169,182,185,223,226,249,255,264,268,271,279,284,287,349,359,363,366,422,425,428,434,438,441,444,535,538,635,643,722,730,734,737,748,834,840,933,939,1029,1032,1036,1039,1069,1075,1110,1119,1184,1195,1198,1276,1282,1371,1375,1385,1389,1403],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":6,"src":17},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fjavascript\u002Ffp-currying\u002Fisray_notarray_Functional_Programming_--stylize_750_--v_5.2_0eedf977-bd19-4b52-b450-99f7a8125b4e.png",[19,20,22],"h2",{"id":21},"intro","Intro",[12,24,25],{},"Functional Programming is honestly one of the more fun paradigms out there. But why do we even need it? In short, it's about avoiding a bunch of problems — the side effects. So I figured I'd just write a really beginner-friendly, really simple intro to Functional Programming in JavaScript.",[19,27,29],{"id":28},"side-effects","Side Effects",[12,31,32],{},"Before I get into Functional Programming, I want to talk about a couple of things first. The first one is side effects.",[12,34,35],{},"So what's a side effect? You've probably run into the term in a totally different context — when you see a doctor and get cold medicine, the box usually lists the side effects, like headaches, drowsiness, body aches, that kind of thing.",[12,37,38],{},"But a side effect isn't necessarily a bad thing. It can be helpful too. It's just that we mostly use the word to describe the negative stuff. With that cold medicine, the side effects might actually include \"your cold gets better\" along with \"you feel sleepy\".",[40,41,44],"callout",{"title":42,"type":43},"Note","note",[12,45,46],{},"A side effect doesn't mean it's bad — it can be a good thing too.",[12,48,49],{},"So you can think of a side effect as \"when you run some function or perform some action, it ends up modifying the existing state or adds some extra behavior.\" Stuff like a global variable getting changed, or printing out a system message — those all count as side effects.",[12,51,52,53,57],{},"At this point you might be scratching your head — why would printing a message (",[54,55,56],"code",{},"console.log()",") count as a side effect? Let's look at a quick example, that should make it clearer.",[59,60,65],"pre",{"className":61,"code":62,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","function sayHello(name) {\n  console.log('Say');\n  return 'Hello' + name;;\n}\n\nsayHello('Ray');\n\u002F\u002F Say\n\u002F\u002F Hello Ray\n","js","",[54,66,67,91,109,124,130,137,150,157],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,69,72,76,80,84,88],"span",{"class":70,"line":71},"line",1,[68,73,75],{"class":74},"sOudu","function",[68,77,79],{"class":78},"scAaK"," sayHello",[68,81,83],{"class":82},"s8XSl","(",[68,85,87],{"class":86},"syBk-","name",[68,89,90],{"class":82},") {\n",[68,92,94,97,100,102,106],{"class":70,"line":93},2,[68,95,96],{"class":82},"  console.",[68,98,99],{"class":78},"log",[68,101,83],{"class":82},[68,103,105],{"class":104},"sWayO","'Say'",[68,107,108],{"class":82},");\n",[68,110,112,115,118,121],{"class":70,"line":111},3,[68,113,114],{"class":74},"  return",[68,116,117],{"class":104}," 'Hello'",[68,119,120],{"class":74}," +",[68,122,123],{"class":82}," name;;\n",[68,125,127],{"class":70,"line":126},4,[68,128,129],{"class":82},"}\n",[68,131,133],{"class":70,"line":132},5,[68,134,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},true,"\n",[68,138,140,143,145,148],{"class":70,"line":139},6,[68,141,142],{"class":78},"sayHello",[68,144,83],{"class":82},[68,146,147],{"class":104},"'Ray'",[68,149,108],{"class":82},[68,151,153],{"class":70,"line":152},7,[68,154,156],{"class":155},"sGBqm","\u002F\u002F Say\n",[68,158,160],{"class":70,"line":159},8,[68,161,162],{"class":155},"\u002F\u002F Hello Ray\n",[12,164,165,166,168],{},"You can see that ",[54,167,142],{}," outputs to the console twice. So... why does that count as a side effect?",[12,170,171,172,174,175,177,178,181],{},"We just called ",[54,173,142],{},", but its computation or execution result shouldn't be affecting anything on the outside. And yet ",[54,176,142],{},", when it runs, ends up outputting something \"outside of the function itself.\" That's exactly why ",[54,179,180],{},"console.log"," is a side effect.",[12,183,184],{},"One thing to note: even if the operation or action isn't wrapped inside a function, as long as it changes the original value it still counts as a side effect.",[59,186,188],{"className":61,"code":187,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"var myName = 'Ray';\n\nmyName = 'Array';\n",[54,189,190,207,211],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,191,192,195,198,201,204],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,193,194],{"class":74},"var",[68,196,197],{"class":82}," myName ",[68,199,200],{"class":74},"=",[68,202,203],{"class":104}," 'Ray'",[68,205,206],{"class":82},";\n",[68,208,209],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,210,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,212,213,216,218,221],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,214,215],{"class":82},"myName ",[68,217,200],{"class":74},[68,219,220],{"class":104}," 'Array'",[68,222,206],{"class":82},[12,224,225],{},"Surprising, right? Even something as ordinary as reassigning a value counts as a kind of side effect. So side effects are super common in JavaScript.",[227,228,229,233,236,243,246],"ul",{},[230,231,232],"li",{},"AJAX",[230,234,235],{},"DOM manipulation",[230,237,238,239,242],{},"Time-related operations (",[54,240,241],{},"setTimeout",")",[230,244,245],{},"Modifying external parameters",[230,247,248],{},"...and so on",[12,250,251,252,254],{},"Kind of scary, huh — basically all of our everyday dev patterns have side effects in them. But that doesn't mean you should avoid anything with a side effect entirely. The point is to understand and get clear on how they work, so you can dodge some unexpected problems. Otherwise, are you really going to stop using ",[54,253,180],{},"? (lol)",[12,256,257,258,263],{},"A while back I wrote a post, \"",[259,260,262],"a",{"href":261},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20210424\u002F616364031\u002F","What is ESM (ES6 Modules or JavaScript Modules)? (article in Mandarin)",",\" which mentions side-effect modules. So using side effects appropriately, and understanding them, can actually help your development.",[19,265,267],{"id":266},"pure-non-pure-functions","Pure & Non-Pure Functions",[12,269,270],{},"A Pure Function is, well, a pure function. So what's a Pure Function?",[12,272,273,274,278],{},"Before we get there — they say it's always easier to learn the bad habits than the good ones (",[275,276,277],"del",{},"so let's start with the bad one",").",[280,281,283],"h3",{"id":282},"non-pure-functions","Non-Pure Functions",[12,285,286],{},"A Non-Pure Function is an impure function. So what makes a function impure? Let's look at a simple Non-Pure Function example:",[59,288,290],{"className":61,"code":289,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"var myName =  'Ray';\n\nfunction sayHello() {\n  console.log('Hello' + myName);\n}\n\nsayHello();\n",[54,291,292,305,309,318,334,338,342],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,293,294,296,298,300,303],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,295,194],{"class":74},[68,297,197],{"class":82},[68,299,200],{"class":74},[68,301,302],{"class":104},"  'Ray'",[68,304,206],{"class":82},[68,306,307],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,308,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,310,311,313,315],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,312,75],{"class":74},[68,314,79],{"class":78},[68,316,317],{"class":82},"() {\n",[68,319,320,322,324,326,329,331],{"class":70,"line":126},[68,321,96],{"class":82},[68,323,99],{"class":78},[68,325,83],{"class":82},[68,327,328],{"class":104},"'Hello'",[68,330,120],{"class":74},[68,332,333],{"class":82}," myName);\n",[68,335,336],{"class":70,"line":132},[68,337,129],{"class":82},[68,339,340],{"class":70,"line":139},[68,341,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,343,344,346],{"class":70,"line":152},[68,345,142],{"class":78},[68,347,348],{"class":82},"();\n",[12,350,351,352,354,355,358],{},"The code above looks perfectly normal and obvious, but in reality ",[54,353,142],{}," reaches directly for a global variable. And in this situation, some other operation could end up polluting the ",[54,356,357],{},"myName"," variable. That's why it's a Non-Pure Function — and Non-Pure Functions can lead to side effects.",[280,360,362],{"id":361},"pure-functions","Pure Functions",[12,364,365],{},"So what's a Pure Function? If we tweak the earlier example, it becomes this:",[59,367,369],{"className":61,"code":368,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"function sayHello(name) {\n  return 'Hello' + name;\n}\n\nconst myName = sayHello('Ray');\n",[54,370,371,383,394,398,402],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,372,373,375,377,379,381],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,374,75],{"class":74},[68,376,79],{"class":78},[68,378,83],{"class":82},[68,380,87],{"class":86},[68,382,90],{"class":82},[68,384,385,387,389,391],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,386,114],{"class":74},[68,388,117],{"class":104},[68,390,120],{"class":74},[68,392,393],{"class":82}," name;\n",[68,395,396],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,397,129],{"class":82},[68,399,400],{"class":70,"line":126},[68,401,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,403,404,407,411,414,416,418,420],{"class":70,"line":132},[68,405,406],{"class":74},"const",[68,408,410],{"class":409},"stw71"," myName",[68,412,413],{"class":74}," =",[68,415,79],{"class":78},[68,417,83],{"class":82},[68,419,147],{"class":104},[68,421,108],{"class":82},[12,423,424],{},"A Pure Function sticks to one principle: one input, one output. That's a Pure Function.",[12,426,427],{},"So a Pure Function follows this rule:",[429,430,431],"blockquote",{},[12,432,433],{},"one input, one output",[19,435,437],{"id":436},"higher-order-functions","Higher-Order Functions",[12,439,440],{},"A Higher-Order Function, also called a HOF, is basically a function that can be passed into another function, or returns a function. Satisfy either of those two conditions and it's a Higher-Order Function.",[12,442,443],{},"I know that's still pretty abstract, so let's look at some example code. First up, \"a function can be passed into a function.\"",[59,445,447],{"className":61,"code":446,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"function fn(callback) {\n  console.log('fn');\n}\n\nfunction HOF(callback) {\n  console.log('HOF');\n  callback();\n}\n\nHOF(fn);\n",[54,448,449,463,476,480,484,497,510,517,521,526],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,450,451,453,456,458,461],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,452,75],{"class":74},[68,454,455],{"class":78}," fn",[68,457,83],{"class":82},[68,459,460],{"class":86},"callback",[68,462,90],{"class":82},[68,464,465,467,469,471,474],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,466,96],{"class":82},[68,468,99],{"class":78},[68,470,83],{"class":82},[68,472,473],{"class":104},"'fn'",[68,475,108],{"class":82},[68,477,478],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,479,129],{"class":82},[68,481,482],{"class":70,"line":126},[68,483,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,485,486,488,491,493,495],{"class":70,"line":132},[68,487,75],{"class":74},[68,489,490],{"class":78}," HOF",[68,492,83],{"class":82},[68,494,460],{"class":86},[68,496,90],{"class":82},[68,498,499,501,503,505,508],{"class":70,"line":139},[68,500,96],{"class":82},[68,502,99],{"class":78},[68,504,83],{"class":82},[68,506,507],{"class":104},"'HOF'",[68,509,108],{"class":82},[68,511,512,515],{"class":70,"line":152},[68,513,514],{"class":78},"  callback",[68,516,348],{"class":82},[68,518,519],{"class":70,"line":159},[68,520,129],{"class":82},[68,522,524],{"class":70,"line":523},9,[68,525,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,527,529,532],{"class":70,"line":528},10,[68,530,531],{"class":78},"HOF",[68,533,534],{"class":82},"(fn);\n",[12,536,537],{},"Or this:",[59,539,541],{"className":61,"code":540,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"const fn = (callback) => {\n  console.log('fn');\n}\n\nconst HOF = (callback) => {\n  console.log('HOF');\n  callback();\n}\n\nHOF(fn);\n",[54,542,543,565,577,581,585,603,615,621,625,629],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,544,545,547,549,551,554,556,559,562],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,546,406],{"class":74},[68,548,455],{"class":78},[68,550,413],{"class":74},[68,552,553],{"class":82}," (",[68,555,460],{"class":86},[68,557,558],{"class":82},") ",[68,560,561],{"class":74},"=>",[68,563,564],{"class":82}," {\n",[68,566,567,569,571,573,575],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,568,96],{"class":82},[68,570,99],{"class":78},[68,572,83],{"class":82},[68,574,473],{"class":104},[68,576,108],{"class":82},[68,578,579],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,580,129],{"class":82},[68,582,583],{"class":70,"line":126},[68,584,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,586,587,589,591,593,595,597,599,601],{"class":70,"line":132},[68,588,406],{"class":74},[68,590,490],{"class":78},[68,592,413],{"class":74},[68,594,553],{"class":82},[68,596,460],{"class":86},[68,598,558],{"class":82},[68,600,561],{"class":74},[68,602,564],{"class":82},[68,604,605,607,609,611,613],{"class":70,"line":139},[68,606,96],{"class":82},[68,608,99],{"class":78},[68,610,83],{"class":82},[68,612,507],{"class":104},[68,614,108],{"class":82},[68,616,617,619],{"class":70,"line":152},[68,618,514],{"class":78},[68,620,348],{"class":82},[68,622,623],{"class":70,"line":159},[68,624,129],{"class":82},[68,626,627],{"class":70,"line":523},[68,628,136],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":135},[68,630,631,633],{"class":70,"line":528},[68,632,531],{"class":78},[68,634,534],{"class":82},[12,636,637,638,642],{},"Both of those are functions being passed into a function. As for the other case, returning a function — clever you has probably already figured out what does that. Yep, it's a ",[259,639,641],{"href":640},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20201220\u002F3559993634\u002F","closure"," (article in Mandarin).",[59,644,646],{"className":61,"code":645,"language":63,"meta":64,"style":64},"function closure() {\n  console.log('closure');\n  return function (myName) {\n    console.log('myName is', myName);\n  }\n}\n\nclosure()('Ray');\n",[54,647,648,657,670,683,698,703,707,711],{"__ignoreMap":64},[68,649,650,652,655],{"class":70,"line":71},[68,651,75],{"class":74},[68,653,654],{"class":78}," closure",[68,656,317],{"class":82},[68,658,659,661,663,665,668],{"class":70,"line":93},[68,660,96],{"class":82},[68,662,99],{"class":78},[68,664,83],{"class":82},[68,666,667],{"class":104},"'closure'",[68,669,108],{"class":82},[68,671,672,674,677,679,681],{"class":70,"line":111},[68,673,114],{"class":74},[68,675,676],{"class":74}," function",[68,678,553],{"class":82},[68,680,357],{"class":86},[68,682,90],{"class":82},[68,684,685,688,690,692,695],{"class":70,"line":126},[68,686,687],{"class":82},"    console.",[68,689,99],{"class":78},[68,691,83],{"class":82},[68,693,694],{"class":104},"'myName is'",[68,696,697],{"class":82},", myName);\n",[68,699,700],{"class":70,"line":132},[68,701,702],{"class":82},"  }\n",[68,704,705